 {"id":"caam-ela","title":"Implement device code auth for Codex provider","description":"# Pass --device-auth flag to Codex login

## What (Simplified)

When user runs \`caam login codex <profile> --device-code\`, pass \`--device-auth\` to the underlying \`codex login\` command.

## Why

Codex CLI natively supports device code flow. We just need to pass the flag through. No new auth modes, no new interfaces - just flag passthrough.

## Implementation (Simple)

### File: internal/provider/codex/codex.go

Update loginWithOAuth to accept a deviceCode parameter:

\`\`\`go
func (p *Provider) Login(ctx context.Context, prof *profile.Profile, opts ...LoginOption) error {
    // ... existing mode dispatch ...
    return p.loginWithOAuth(ctx, prof, opts...)
}

func (p *Provider) loginWithOAuth(ctx context.Context, prof *profile.Profile, opts ...LoginOption) error {
    args := []string{"login"}

    // Check if device-code was requested
    for _, opt := range opts {
        if opt.DeviceCode {
            args = append(args, "--device-auth")
        }
    }

    cmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, "codex", args...)
    // ... rest unchanged ...
}
\`\`\`

Or even simpler - just check for an environment variable or context value set by the CLI command.

## What We're NOT Doing

- ❌ No new AuthModeDeviceCode stored in profile
- ❌ No DeviceCodeProvider interface needed  
- ❌ No changes to profile.yaml schema

The auth mode in the profile stays "oauth" - device code is just an alternative way to complete the OAuth flow.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] \`caam login codex work --device-code\` triggers device code flow
- [ ] Profile remains AuthModeOAuth (device code is flow variant, not mode)
- [ ] Auth file saved to correct location
